what is taint and tolerations?

taint on node

kubectl taint nodes <node-name> key=value:Effect

Three effects:

Effect              Behavior
NoSchedule          New pods do not tolerate the taint won't be scheduled on the node (existing pods stay)
PreferNoSchedule    Kubernetes tries to avoid scheduling, but not guaranteed (existing pods stay)
NoExecute           New pods won't schedule AND existing pods are evicted if they don't tolerate it

Tolerations (applied to Pods)

NoSchedule 

Node1 has taint: env=prod:NoSchedule

New pod (no toleration):
  Kubernetes checks node1 → has taint ❌
  Cannot schedule here
        ↓
  Checks other nodes
        ↓
  If other nodes available → schedules there ✅
  If NO other nodes → stays PENDING ⏳
  Never goes to Node1 ❌

spec:
  tolerations:
  - key: "env"
    operator: "Equal"
    value: "prod"
    effect: "NoSchedule"


Remove a Taint

kubectl taint nodes node1 env=prod:NoSchedule-   # note the trailing dash

---------------------------------------
NoExecute

Step 1 — Before taint:
  Node1: Pod A running ✅

Step 2 — Taint applied:
  Node1: env=prod:NoExecute

Step 3 — Pod A (no toleration):
  Kubernetes checks → no toleration ❌
  Pod A evicted from Node1
  Pod A moves to another node

Step 4 — New Pod B (has toleration):
  Kubernetes checks → has toleration ✅
  Pod B schedules on Node1
  Pod B stays running

tolerations:
  - key: "env"
    operator: "Equal"
    value: "prod"
    effect: "NoExecute"
    tolerationSeconds: 60    # ← stay for 60 seconds then evict
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
PreferNoSchedul

Cluster has 3 nodes:

Node1 → taint: PreferNoSchedule
Node2 → no taint
Node3 → no taint

New pod (no toleration):
  Kubernetes prefers Node2 or Node3 ✅
  Avoids Node1 if possible

If Node2 and Node3 are FULL:
  Kubernetes schedules on Node1 anyway ✅
  (no choice!)
